🔹 Common Ways to Use ResponseEntity

1. Return with Status Code:

	@GetMapping("/success")
	public ResponseEntity<String> success() {
	    return new ResponseEntity<>("Success", HttpStatus.OK);
	}

2. Return Object as JSON:
	@GetMapping("/user")
	public ResponseEntity<User> getUser() {
	    User user = new User(1, "John");
	    return ResponseEntity.ok(user);
	}
	Spring automatically converts the object to JSON.


3. Custom Status Codes:
	@PostMapping("/create")
	public ResponseEntity<String> create() {
	    return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.CREATED)
	                         .body("Created successfully");
	}

4. Return No Content
	@DeleteMapping("/delete/{id}")
	public ResponseEntity<Void> delete(@PathVariable int id) {
	    return ResponseEntity.noContent().build();
	}

5. Return Headers:
	@GetMapping("/headers")
	public ResponseEntity<String> headers() {
	    return ResponseEntity.ok()
	            .header("Custom-Header", "Value")
	            .body("With headers");
	}

6. Handle Not Found:
	@GetMapping("/user/{id}")
	public ResponseEntity<User> getUser(@PathVariable int id) {
	    User user = userService.findById(id);
	
	    if (user == null) {
	        return ResponseEntity.status(HttpStatus.NOT_FOUND).build();
	    }
	
	    return ResponseEntity.ok(user);
	}

🔹 Why Use ResponseEntity?
	`Control HTTP response fully
	Return proper REST status codes
	Add custom headers
	Handle errors cleanly`